'''Ogushi Shrine''' (おぐしじんじゃ) is a shrine in Kōya-machi, {{ill|lt=Aoi-ku|Q1131483|WD=Q1131483|1=Aoi-ku, Shizuoka}}, {{ill|lt=Shizuoka|Q174691|WD=Q174691|1=Shizuoka (city)}}, {{ill|lt=Shizuoka Prefecture|Q131320|WD=Q131320|1=Shizuoka Prefecture}}<ref>[http://www.shizuoka-jinjacho.or.jp/shokai/jinja.php?id=4406004 小梳神社] - Shizuoka Prefecture Association of Shinto Shrines</ref>.

=== Overview ===
It is enshrined just northwest of the north exit of JR {{ill|lt=Shizuoka Station|Q801440|WD=Q801440|1=Shizuoka Station}}, on the north side along Gofuku-chō-dōri.

Its foundation is unknown, but it is an old shrine identified with a same-named {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}<ref name="oz">[https://humizuki.com/omaturi_zanmai/sight/jinja/sizuoka/ogusi.htm 小梳神社] - Omatsuri Zanmai</ref><ref name="genbu">[https://genbu.net/data/suruga/ogusi_title.htm 小梳神社] - Genshōshi</ref>.

It is also called Shōshōinomiya and was revered by the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Imagawa clan|1=UNKNOWN}}<ref name="s-kanko2">[https://www.visit-shizuoka.com/t/oogosho400/study/07_05.htm 紺屋町と少将井社〔小梳神社〕と代官屋敷] - Suruga Planning and Tourism Bureau</ref>.

It is also known as a shrine where the young {{ill|lt=Tokugawa Ieyasu|Q171977|WD=Q171977|1=Tokugawa Ieyasu}} (Takechiyo) prayed for lasting martial fortune. It once stood at the castle deputy’s residence in the third bailey of {{ill|lt=Sunpu Castle|Q1038629|WD=Q1038629|1=Sunpu Castle}} (present Shizuoka City History Museum, formerly Aoba Elementary School), but with expansion of Sunpu Castle in the Edo period it was moved via Araya-machi (present Miyuki-chō to Tenma-chō) to its current site (Kōya-machi)<ref name="s-kanko2"/><ref name="s-kanko">[https://www.visit-shizuoka.com/spots/detail.php?kanko=543#:~:text=%E5%BE%B3%E5%B7%9D%E5%AE%B6%E5%BA%B7%E3%81%AE%E5%B9%BC%E5%B0%91%E6%9C%9F,%E5%BA%87%E8%AD%B7%E3%82%92%E5%8F%97%E3%81%91%E3%81%BE%E3%81%97%E3%81%9F%25E3%2580%2582 小梳神社] - Suruga Planning and Tourism Bureau</ref><ref name="in">[http://www.ieyasu-net.com/shiseki/shizuoka/07shizuokashi/0002.html 小梳神社] - Nationwide Ieyasu Network</ref>.

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 40 ({{ill|lt=1907|Q2048|WD=Q2048|1=1907}}), it was ranked as a prefectural shrine<ref name="oz"/>.

